Raw dev notes -- Kicking off RAG and Taming Browser Uploads

Okay, so this past week has been a bit of a split focus, but in a good way. On one hand, I'm finally diving headfirst into building out my own personal RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) system. The goal here is to create a smart assistant that can pull from *my* scattered knowledge base – all my notes, articles I've read, thoughts I've jotted down – and give me coherent answers or summaries. It's a big undertaking, but the idea of having a personalized brain extension is super motivating.

The other thread is a utility project, a browser automation API wrapper. This thing exists because sometimes you just can't get the data you need via a clean API. You have to interact with a website like a human, and that often means dealing with forms, clicks, and especially file uploads. This wrapper is meant to abstract away some of that browser-level pain.

So, what actually happened?

For the **Browser Automation API Wrapper**, I finally tackled a pretty gnarly feature: adding a `POST /sources/file` endpoint that handles browser-native uploads. This isn't just sending a file via an API request; this is literally telling the headless browser to *find* the `<input type="file">` element on a webpage, click it, select a file from the local system, and then trigger whatever change events the website expects. It's crucial for those sites that have client-side validation or specific JavaScript listeners tied to the file input.

Then, the big one: **rag-core**. This week saw its `Initial commit`. This is the very foundation of the RAG system. Right now, it's mostly project structure, some initial interfaces, and probably a very basic proof-of-concept for how I'll handle embeddings or retrieval. It's the blank canvas, the core logic that everything else will build upon.

Finally, the **RAG Knowledge Base Pipeline** had a small but satisfying update: `sync: 0 new posts, 1 comment updates`. This pipeline is the ingestion layer for my RAG system, responsible for pulling in data from various sources and keeping the knowledge base fresh. Seeing that log message, even for just one comment update, means the sync process is running, it's monitoring its sources, and it's successfully detecting and processing changes.

The hardest part this week was definitely getting that browser-native file upload working reliably. Browser automation is always a game of whack-a-mole. Different websites use different frameworks, sometimes there's a shadow DOM, sometimes the file input is hidden and triggered by a custom button. Debugging headless browser interactions is a special kind of hell – you're trying to figure out why a "click" didn't register or why a file wasn't "selected" when you can't even see what's happening in real-time without adding a bunch of debug screenshots. It took a lot of trial and error to get it robust enough.

Starting `rag-core` was also a mix of excitement and a little bit of overwhelm. The blank page problem is real. Deciding on the initial architecture, what libraries to pull in, how to structure the data for maximum flexibility later – it's a lot of upfront thinking that feels slow, but I know it's critical.

Personally, it felt really good to finally get that file upload working. It's one of those persistent little thorns in the side of web automation, and having a robust solution for it feels like a small victory. And seeing the RAG pipeline actually *do* something, even just a single comment update, was a huge morale boost. It's a tiny step, but it confirms the plumbing is working, and that's a big deal for a complex system like this. It reminds me that even small, consistent progress adds up. I'm learning a ton about the practicalities of building a RAG system, not just the theoretical concepts.

Next up: Expanding `rag-core`'s capabilities and integrating more data sources into the pipeline.
